T1  - Welfare dominance and the design of excise taxation in the Côte d'ivoire
AU  - Yitzhaki, Shlomo
AU  - Thirsk, Wayne
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 33
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 18
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/07/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(90)90002-S
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789090002S
AB  - Designing optimum excise taxes has been shown to require information, not easily obtained, about the nature of an economy's social welfare function. If instead of seeking the best excise tax system, policymakers ask what is a better excise tax system, it is possible to use the concept of marginal conditional welfare dominance and avoid the need for strong value judgements. An excise tax base is welfare dominant if virtually all plausible social welfare functions would approve relatively higher taxes on that base. Applying this concept to the Côte d'Ivoire we present an equity argument for greater reliance on electricity and telephone excises and indicate that administrative and efficiency considerations might also favor this choice.
ER  - 

