T1  - Does regulation improve small farmers' access to Brazilian rural credit?
AU  - Anderson, Julie
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 33
IS  - 1
SP  - 67
EP  - 87
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/07/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(90)90006-W
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789090006W
AB  - Brazilian policymakers attempted to counter the inherent tendency for concentration in subsidized rural credit programs by requiring banks to lend a specified volume to small farmers. Inferences about the regulation's success are drawn from farm-level, panel data from São Paulo in the early 1980s. Membership in the target group should have a positive effect in an ‘access rule’, relating farmers' characteristics to their probability of receiving credit. When allowing for time-invariant individual effects, possibly correlated with target group indicators, tests indicate that the regulation had no effect. Subsidiary results cast doubt on the efficacy of a broader set of regulations.
